<PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="Publisher" Owner="NLM"><PMID Version="1">40413069</PMID><DateRevised><Year>2025</Year><Month>05</Month><Day>24</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print-Electronic"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Print">0013-7006</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><PubDate><Year>2025</Year><Month>May</Month><Day>23</Day></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>L'Encephale</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Encephale</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>[Towards an equipped psychiatry].</ArticleTitle><ELocationID EIdType="pii" ValidYN="Y">S0013-7006(25)00096-X</ELocationID><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1016/j.encep.2025.03.002</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText>The article by Moizard and Geoffroy highlights the importance of an integrated approach in psychiatry, emphasizing the need to move beyond the dichotomy between the somatic and the psychic. In their commentary, the authors advocated for precision psychiatry, which leverages the latest scientific and technological advancements. They underscored the necessity of equipping psychiatry with advanced technologies, particularly neuroimaging, artificial intelligence, and digital twins. These tools enable a more rigorous and personalized approach to mental healthcare grounded in specific biomarkers and precise modeling of psychiatric disorders.</AbstractText><CopyrightInformation>Copyright &#xa9; 2025 L'Enc&#xe9;phale, Paris. Published by Elsevier Masson SAS. All rights reserved.</CopyrightInformation></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Jehel</LastName><ForeName>Louis</ForeName><Initials>L</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Service de psychiatrie, CHU d'Amiens-Picardie, universit&#xe9; de Picardie-Jules Verne, 1, rue du Professeur Christian-Cabrol, 80000 Amiens, France.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Guid&#xe8;re</LastName><ForeName>Mathieu</ForeName><Initials>M</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Inserm, U1018, CES